other uses
File:Tracy Caldwell Dyson in Cupola ISS.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Tracy Caldwell Dyson viewing Earth from the ISS Cupola, 2010
File:Astronaut Mae Jemison Working in Spacelab-J (7544385084).jpg|thumb|300px|Mae Jemison in Spacelab on STS-47, 1992
File:ISS27 Catherine Coleman plays a flute.jpg|thumb|300px|Female astronaut Catherine Coleman playing a flute aboard ISS, 2011

Women of many nationalities have worked in space. The first woman in space, Soviet cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova, flew in 1963. Space flight programs were slow to employ women, and only began to include them from the 1980s. Most women in space have been United States citizens, with missions on the Space Shuttle and on the International Space Station. Three countries maintain active space programs that include women: China, Russia, and the United States of America. In addition, a number of other countries — Canada, France, India, Iran, Italy, Japan, South Korea, and the United Kingdom — have sent women into orbit or space on Russian or US missions.

Women in space face many of the same challenges faced by men: physical difficulties posed by non-Earth conditions and psychological stresses of isolation and separation. Scientific studies on female amphibians and non-human mammals generally show no adverse effect from short space missions, although the effect of extended space travel on human female reproduction is not known.

Women in space programs
File:RIAN archive 581339 Pilot-cosmonaut Valentina Vladimirovna Tereshkova.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Valentina Tereshkova, the first woman in space, 1969
Although the first woman flew into space in 1963, very early in manned space exploration|crewed space exploration, it would not be until almost 20 years later that another flew.

And while a number of American women underwent the astronaut selection process in the early 1960s - and passed - they were not eligible to be astronauts: All astronauts were required to be military test pilots, a career not available to women at the time.<ref name=flats>cite web|last1= Weitekamp  |first1=Margaret A. |last2=Garber |first2=Steve |url=https://history.nasa.gov/flats.html |title=Lovelace’s Woman in Space Program |publisher=NASA </ref>

NASA opened the space program to female applicants in 1978, in response to the new anti-discrimination laws of the time. When Sally Ride, the first US astronaut first went to space, the press asked her questions about her reproductive organs and whether she would cry if things went wrong on the job.<ref name=autogenerated1>cite web|last=Ryan |first=Michael |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20085312,00.html |title=A Ride in Space – NASA, Sally Ride |work=People |accessdate=December 5, 2013</ref>

Women with children also face questions about how they would compare to traditional expectations of motherhood.<ref name=spacemom>cite web | url = http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/expeditions/expedition36/astro_mom_karen.html | publisher = NASA | title = Astronaut Mom Karen Nyberg Prepares for Mission and Motherhood 255 Miles Up | work = International Space Station | date = May 9, 2013</ref> Shannon Lucid, one of the first batch of female US astronauts, remembers questions by the press on how her children would handle her being a mother in space.<ref name=Foster-146>cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=mqjORRNpo-cC&pg=PA146| first = Amy E. | last = Foster | title = Integrating Women Into the Astronaut Corps: Politics and Logistics at NASA, 1972-2004 | page = 146 | publisher = The Johns Hopkins University Press | location = Baltimore, Maryland | isbn = 978-1-4214-0195-9</ref> Women are also often expected to be the ones mainly responsible for childrearing, which can impact their career.<ref name=kramer>cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/03/world/europe/parenting-from-earths-orbit.html?_r=1& | first = A. | last = Kramer | title = Parenting From Earth's Orbit | newspaper = The New York Times | date = July 2, 2013 </ref>

=Soviet Union (includes Russia)=
The first woman in space was a Soviet cosmonaut. Valentina Tereshkova launched with the Vostok 6 mission on June 16, 1963. The first woman to walk in space was also a cosmonaut: Svetlana Savitskaya was on her second mission when she space-walked on July 17, 1984 as part of Salyut 7-EP2.

Svetlana Savitskaya was the first woman to go on extravehicular activity (EVA) — after launching on Soyuz T-12 on July 25, 1984 — and the second woman overall to go into space.<ref name=WomenInSpace-NASA>cite web | url = https://history.nasa.gov/women.html | title = Women in Space | work = NASA History Program Office | first = Stephen | last = Garber | origyear = July 6, 2015 |date= July 2017 | publisher = National Aeronautics and Space Administration | access-date = March 5, 2018</ref>

Post-Soviet Russia
Russian Yelena V. Kondakova became the first woman to travel for both the Soyuz programme and on the Space Shuttle. Yelena Serova became the first female Russian cosmonaut to visit the International Space Station on 26 September 2014.<ref>cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-29372277| title=First Russian woman in International Space Station mission| accessdate=6 October 2014 |work=BBC News |date=26 September 2014</ref>

The Russian space program has also hosted international cosmonauts. Helen Sharman from the United Kingdom (1991), Claudie Haigneré from France (1996 and 2001), Anousheh Ansari from Iran (2006), Yi So-yeon of South Korea (2008) and Samantha Cristoforetti from Italy (2014) and six Amen have entered space as part of the Soyuz programme.

=United States=
File:STS-41-D_Crew_Enjoying_Space_-_GPN-2004-00024.jpg|thumb|Judith Resnik as mission specialist in orbit onboard Space Shuttle Discovery in 1984. She died less than a year and a half later onboard the Challenger.
File:First Six Women Astronauts with Rescue Ball - GPN-2002-000207.jpg|thumb|From left to right, Margaret Rhea Seddon|Margaret R. (Rhea) Seddon, Kathryn D. Sullivan, Judith Resnik, Sally K. Ride, Anna L. Fisher, and Shannon W. Lucid—the first six female astronauts of the United States.
File:ISS-48 EVA-2 (a) Kate Rubins.jpg|thumb|U.S. astronaut Kathleen Rubins outside ISS on spacewalk
File:ISS-48 EVA (j) Kate Rubins.jpg|thumb|Kathleen Rubins on EVA, 2016
The United States did not have a woman in space until 1983, when astronaut Sally Ride launched with the STS-7|seventh Space Shuttle mission. Since then more than 40 American women have entered space. Most served on the various Space Shuttle flights from 1983 to 2011.

Sally Ride was the third woman overall to go into space, launching on the Space Shuttle.<ref name=WomenInSpace-NASA /> Ride served on the STS-7 from June 18 to 24 in 1983.<ref name=WomenInSpace-NASA /> Judith Resnik was the second American woman in space, after Sally Ride, and the fourth woman overall in space, as a mission specialist on the STS-41-D|maiden voyage of Space Shuttle Discovery|''Discovery'', from August to September 1984,<ref>cite web| last = Wade| first = Mark| title = Resnik| url = http://www.astronautix.com/astros/resnik.htm| accessdate = 2009-11-21| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091008151817/http://www.astronautix.com/astros/resnik.htm| archivedate = 2009-10-08| df = 
</ref> dying less than a year and a half later when the Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' was destroyed.  The first U.S. woman to go on an EVA was Kathryn D. Sullivan|Kathryn ("Kathy") Sullivan on the STS-41-G, which launched on October 11, 1984.<ref name=WomenInSpace-NASA /> The first woman to be on an ISS expedition crew was Susan Helms on Expedition 2, which lasted from March 2001 until August 2001.<ref name=WomenInSpace-NASA /> United States NASA astronaut Kathleen Rubins became the 60th woman to fly in space when she launched to the International Space Station on July 6, 2016, serving as a flight engineer on Expedition 48 and Expedition 49.<ref name="Pearlman">cite news|title=Station-Bound NASA Astronaut is the 60th Woman to Fly into Space|url=http://www.space.com/33355-kate-rubins-60th-woman-in-space.html|accessdate=7 July 2016|publisher=SPACE.com</ref> She returned in October 2016, having spent 12 hours and 46 minutes on EVA and 115 days in space and 12 hours and 46 minutes in space as part of these missions.<ref name=bio-KathleenRubins>cite web | url = https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/kathleen-rubins/biography | title = Kathleen "Kate" Rubins (PH.D.) NASA Astronaut | date = December 5, 2016 | editor-first = Melanie | editor-last = Whiting | author-first = Brian | author-last = Dunbar | work = NASA | publisher = National Aeronautics and Space Administration | access-date = January 7, 2016</ref> During her stay on ISS she also conducted numerous experiments including some in the area of biology.<ref name=bio-KathleenRubins /> She was the first woman, and the first person, to DNA sequencing|sequence DNA in space.<ref>cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/science/sdut-kate-rubins-DNA-2016aug29-story.html|title=UCSD alumna first to sequence DNA in space|last=Robbins|first=Gary|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|date=August 29, 2016|accessdate=October 26, 2016</ref>

In addition to U.S. citizens, US rockets have launched international astronauts. Roberta Bondar (in 1992) and Julie Payette (in 1999 and 2009) from Canada, Kalpana Chawla of India (1997 and 2003), and Chiaki Mukai (in 1994 and 1998) and Naoko Yamazaki (in 2010) of Japan flew as part of the US space program.

A number of other high-profile women have contributed to interest in space programs. In the early 2000s, Lori Garver initiated a project to increase the visibility and viability of commercial spaceflight with the "AstroMom" project. She aimed to fill an unused Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz seat bound for the International Space Station because "…creating a spacefaring civilization was one of the most important things we could do in our lifetime.”<ref name=foust>cite web | url = http://www.thespacereview.com/article/1003/1 | first = Jeff | last = Foust | title = AstroMom and Basstronaut, revisited | date = November 19, 2007 | publisher = The Space Review</ref>

=Canada=
File:Astronaut Julie Payette looks through an overhead window on Space Shuttle Endeavour.jpg|thumb|Canadian astronaut Julie Payette in space in 2009 (STS-127)
Roberta Bondar was the first Canadian woman in space, and the Marc Garneau|second Canadian. She flew on the Space Shuttle Space Shuttle Discovery|''Discovery'' in January 1992.<ref>cite web |url=http://www.city.sault-ste-marie.on.ca/library/Bondar_Bio.html | title=Dr. Roberta Lynn Bondar: Canada's First Female Astronaut | work = Sault History Online | publisher=Sault Ste. Marie Public Library | date = 2008 | accessdate=2011-04-17</ref>

Another Canadian woman astronaut is Julie Payette from Montreal. Payette was part of the crew of STS-96, on the Space Shuttle ''Discovery'' from May 27 to June 6, 1999. During the mission, the crew performed the first manual docking of the Shuttle to the International Space Station, and delivered four tons of logistics and supplies to the station. On ''Endeavour'' in 2009 for STS-127, Payette served as a mission specialist. Her main responsibility was to operate the Canadarm robotic arm from the space station.<ref name="inventive">cite web |url=http://www.inventivewomen.com/library/library_julie_payette_que.shtml |title=Inventive Women Biographies: Julie Payette | work = Inventive Women | date = 2006 | publisher = Inventive Women Inc. | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090217154337/http://inventivewomen.com/library/library_julie_payette_que.shtml | archive-date = February 17, 2009</ref> Payette was sworn in as the 29th Governor-General of Canada on October 2, 2017.

=Japan=
File:STS131 Yamazaki2 Sept09.jpg|thumb|Naoko Yamazaki at NASA Johnson Space Center, 2009
In 1985, Chiaki Mukai was selected as one of three Japanese Payload Specialist candidates for the First Material Processing Test (Spacelab-J) that flew aboard STS-47 in 1992. She also served as a back-up payload specialist for the Neurolab (STS-90) mission. Mukai has logged over 566 hours in space. She flew aboard STS-65 in 1994 and STS-95 in 1998. She is the first Japanese woman to fly in space, and the first Japanese citizen to fly twice.<ref name="NASA-bio">cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/PS/mukai.html|title=Astronaut Bio: Chiaki Mukai|publisher=NASA|date=October 2003</ref>

Naoko Yamazaki became the second Japanese woman to fly into space with her launch on April 5, 2010, Yamazaki entered space on the shuttle ''Discovery'' as part of mission STS-131.  She returned to Earth on April 20, 2010.<ref>Harwood, William. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/06/science/space/06shuttle.html?hp "Shuttle Lifts Off for Space Station"], ''The New York Times'', New York City, April 5, 2010. Retrieved on 2010-04-05.</ref><ref name="Japan1">cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUKTRE4AA12820081111 |title=Astronaut set to become Japan's first mum in space |accessdate=November 18, 2008 |publisher=Reuters UK |author=Reuters |date=November 11, 2008</ref><ref name="jaxa">cite web |url=http://www.jaxa.jp/topics/2008/11_e.html |title=Naoko Yamazaki to become second Japanese female astronaut to fly to space |last=JAXA |date=November 11, 2008 |publisher=Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency |accessdate=2008-11-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213214938/http://www.jaxa.jp/topics/2008/11_e.html |archivedate=December 13, 2009 |df= </ref><ref name="manifest">Cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/structure/iss_manifest.html |title=Consolidated Launch Manifest |accessdate=October 25, 2008 |publisher=NASA |year=2008 |author=NASA</ref> Yamazaki worked on ISS hardware development projects in the 1990s. She is an aerospace engineer and also holds a Masters degree in that field.<ref name=bio-NaokoYamazaki>cite web | url = https://www.nasa.gov/externalflash/the_shuttle/351.html | title = Naoko Yamazaki, JAXA Astronaut | date = April 2010 | publisher = National Aeronautics and Space Administration | access-date = January 7, 2017</ref> She was selected for astronaut training in 1999 and was certified by 2001.<ref name=bio-NaokoYamazaki /> She was a mission specialist on her 2010 space shuttle flight, and spent 362 hours in space.<ref name=bio-NaokoYamazaki />  Yamazaki worked on robotics and transitioned through the reorganization of Japanese spaceflight organization when 2003 NASDA merged with ISAS (Institute of Space & Astronautic Science) and NAL (National Aerospace Laboratory of Japan).<ref name=bio-NaokoYamazaki />  The new organization was called JAXA (Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency).<ref name=bio-NaokoYamazaki />

=China=
Main|Chinese women in space
In 2012, the Chinese space program sent their first woman to space.
File:LIU Yang CUHK 2012.JPG|thumb|left|Liu Yang (astronaut)|Liu Yang, the first Chinese woman in space
China's first female astronaut candidates, chosen in 2010 from the ranks of fighter pilots, were required to be married mothers.<ref name=china>cite news | url = http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1974793,00.html | first = Hillary | last = Brenhouse | title = China: Female Astronauts Must Be Married with Children | publisher = TIME | date = March 25, 2010</ref> The Chinese stated that married women were "more physically and psychologically mature" and that the rule that they had have had children was because of concerns that spaceflight would harm their reproductive organs (which includes embryos).<ref name=china/> The unknown nature of the effects of spaceflight on women was also noted.<ref name=china/> However, the director of the China Astronaut Centre has stated that marriage is a preference but not a strict limitation.<ref name="Wu Bin interview ">cite web | url=http://english.cntv.cn/program/newsupdate/20120616/107007.shtml | title=Exclusive interview: Astronauts selection process | publisher=CNTV | work=CCTV News | date=June 16, 2012 | accessdate=June 17, 2012</ref> Part of why they were so strict was because it was their first astronaut selection and they were trying be "extra cautious".<ref name=china/>  China's first woman astronaut, Liu Yang (astronaut)|Liu Yang, was married but had no children at the time of her flight in June 2012.<ref>cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/mainland/special/shenzhoujiuhao/content-3/detail_2012_06/13/15244018_0.shtml?_from_ralated |title=女航天员刘洋婆婆：希望媳妇能尽快生个孩子_资讯频道_凤凰网 |trans-title=Mother-in-law of female astronaut Liu Yang: I hope daughter-in-law gives birth to a child as soon as possible | author = 孙兰兰 贾磊 |publisher=News.ifeng.com |date= 2012-06-13|accessdate=2012-06-18</ref><ref name="BBC">cite web|title=China launches space mission with first woman astronaut|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-18458544 | publisher=BBC|accessdate=June 16, 2012|date=June 16, 2012|last=Amos|first=Jonathan</ref>

