Women space tourists
Image:Anousheh Ansari in the ISS.jpg|thumb|left|Ansari holds a plant grown in the Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda Service Module of the International Space Station.
Anousheh Ansari was the fourth overall self-funded Space tourism|space traveler, and the first self-funded woman to fly to the International Space Station. She flew to the station in 2006 on the Soyuz TMA-9 spacecraft.<ref>cite book | url = http://us.macmillan.com/mydreamofstars/AnoushehAnsari | title = My Dream of Stars: From Daughter of Iran to Space Pioneer | author-first = Anousheh | author-last = Ansari | author2-first = Homer | author2-last = Hickam | publisher = St. Martin's Press | date = March 2, 2010 | isbn = 9780230105799</ref> Her mission launched from the Baikonur Cosmodrome on 18 September 2006 at 08:09 Moscow Time|MSD (04:09 Universal Coordinated Time|UTC), docked with the ISS at 09:21 MSD (05:21 UTC) on 20 September, and returned to Earth on 21 April 2007. Soyuz TMA-9 transported two-thirds of ISS Expedition 14 to the space station along with Ansari.<ref name=Ansari-ESA>cite web | url = http://www.esa.int/esaCP/SEMQRH7LURE_index_0.html | title = ESA experiments with spaceflight participant Ansari to ISS | date = 12 September 2006 | work = International Space Center | publisher = European Space Agency | accessdate = 2006-09-22</ref> Ansari performed several experiments on behalf of the European Space Agency.<ref name=Ansari-ESA />

By 2015 four women were classified as "space flight participants": Helen Sharman, Claudie Haigneré (born André-Deshays), Anousheh Ansari, and Yi So-yeon.<ref name=WomenInSpace-NASA />

Deaths
File:Christa McAuliffe and Barbara Morgan - GPN-2002-000004.jpg|thumb|The crew of STS-51-L would perish in the Challenger disaster, including Judith A. Resnik and Christa McAuliffe.

Payload Specialist Christa McAuliffe and mission specialist Judith Resnik became the first women to die on a space mission when the Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' Challenger Disaster|exploded less than 2 minutes after launch with the loss of all hands.<ref name=lathers>cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=CeatsDiyPNAC&pg=PA233| first = Marie | last = Lathers | title = Space Oddities: Women and Outer Space in Popular Film and Culture, 1960-2000 | page = 106 | publisher = The Continuum International Publishing Group | date = 2010 | isbn = 978-1-4411-9049-9</ref><ref>Harvnb|Corrigan|2000|p=123</ref><ref name="NASABio">Cite web|url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/Biographies/challenger.html|title=The Crew of the Challenger Shuttle Mission in 1986|publisher=NASA|date=2004-10-22</ref><ref name="Corrigan40">Harvnb|Corrigan|2000|p=40</ref><ref>Cite book|last=Burgess | first=Colin| last2=Corrigan| first2=Grace George|author-link=Colin Burgess (author)|title=Teacher in space: Christa McAuliffe and the Challenger legacy| location=Lincoln, NE |publisher= University of Nebraska Press |date= 2000|isbn=0-8032-6182-9| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vteUlpMu7IwC</ref>

In the 2003 Space Shuttle Columbia disaster the crew was lost on re-entry, including mission specialists Kalpana Chawla and Laurel Clark.<ref>[https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/reflections-loss-sts-107-space-shuttle-columbia-ten-years-ago]</ref>

Physical effects of space on women
Main|Effect of spaceflight on the human body
File:Weightless hair.jpg|thumb|left|Astronaut Marsha Ivins demonstrates the effects of zero-G on her hair in space
Female astronauts are subject to the same general physical effects of space travel as men. These include physiological changes due to weightlessness such as Spaceflight osteopenia|loss of bone and muscle mass, Health threat from cosmic rays|health threats from cosmic rays, dangers due to vacuum and temperature, and psychological stress.

NASA reports initially argued that menstruation could pose serious health risks or have a negative effect on performance, although it is now dealt with as a matter of routine.<ref name="popsci.com">cite magazine | url = http://www.popsci.com/brief-history-menstruating-in-space | title = A Brief History Of Menstruating In Space: Before women started flying in space, NASA was a little worried they might die having their periods | first = Amy Shira | last = Teitel | date = June 10, 2016 | access-date = January 7, 2017 | magazine = Popular Science | publisher =  Bonnier Corporation</ref><ref name="theatlantic.com">cite magazine | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2016/04/menstruating-in-space/479229/ | title = Women Astronauts: To Menstruate or Not to Menstruate | first = Julie | last = Beck | date = April 21, 2016 | magazine = The Atlantic | access-date = January 7, 2016</ref>

Both men and women are affected by radiation. However, due to the currently used risk models for endometrial, ovarian and breast cancer, women at NASA can currently only spend half as much time on missions as men, which limits their career options compared to men.<ref>cite web | url = http://www.space.com/22252-women-astronauts-radiation-risk.html | title = Female Astronauts Face Discrimination from Space Radiation Concerns, Astronauts Say | first = Miriam | last = Kramer | date = August 27, 2013 | access-date = January 7, 2017 | work = Space.com | publisher = Purch</ref>

Scientific study of pregnancy in space
File:PIA17601-Comparisons-RadiationExposure-MarsTrip-20131209.png|thumb|250px|right|Comparison of radiation Doses including the amount detected on the trip from Earth to Mars by the Radiation assessment detector|RAD on the Mars Science Laboratory|MSL (2011 - 2013).<ref name="SCI-20130531a">cite journal |last=Kerr |first=Richard |title=Radiation Will Make Astronauts' Trip to Mars Even Riskier |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/340/6136/1031.summary |date=31 May 2013 |journal=Science (journal)|Science |volume=340 |number=6136 |page=1031 |doi=10.1126/science.340.6136.1031 |accessdate=31 May 2013 |pmid=23723213</ref><ref name="SCI-20130531b">cite journal |author=Zeitlin, C. |display-authors=etal |title=Measurements of Energetic Particle Radiation in Transit to Mars on the Mars Science Laboratory |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/340/6136/1080.abstract |journal=Science (journal)|Science |date=31 May 2013 |volume=340 |number=6136 |pages=1080–1084 |doi=10.1126/science.1235989 |accessdate=31 May 2013 |bibcode=2013Sci...340.1080Z </ref><ref name="NYT-20130530">cite news |last=Chang |first=Kenneth |title=Data Point to Radiation Risk for Travelers to Mars |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/31/science/space/data-show-higher-cancer-risk-for-mars-astronauts.html |date=30 May 2013 |newspaper =New York Times |accessdate=31 May 2013 </ref><ref name="SN-20130629">cite journal |last=Gelling |first=Cristy|title=Mars trip would deliver big radiation dose; Curiosity instrument confirms expectation of major exposures|url=http://www.sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/350728/description/Mars_trip_would_deliver_big_radiation_dose|volume=183 |issue=13 |page=8 |journal=Science News |date=June 29, 2013 |accessdate=July 8, 2013 </ref>  

=Pregnancy=
NASA has not permitted pregnant astronauts to fly in space,<ref name=Foster-139>Foster, p. 139.</ref> and there have been no pregnant women in space.<ref name=stier/> However, various science experiments have dealt with some aspects of pregnancy.<ref name=stier/>

Exposure to radiation is a concern. For air travel, the United States' Federal Aviation Administration recommends a limit of 1 mSv total for a pregnancy, and no more than 0.5 mSv per month.<ref name=davis>cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_6hymYAgC6MC&pg=PA229| editor-first = Jeffrey R.  | editor-last = Davis | editor2-first =  Robert | editor2-last = Johnson | editor3-first = Jan | editor3-last = Stepanek | editor4-first = Jennifer A. | editor4-last = Fogarty | title = Fundamentals of Aerospace Medicine | date = 2008 | edition = Fourth | pages = 221–230 | accessdate = January 7, 2017</ref> Astronauts on Project Apollo|Apollo and Skylab missions received on average 1.2 mSv/day and 1.4 mSv/day respectively.<ref name = historicalexposure/> Exposures on the International Space Station|ISS average 0.4 mSv per day<ref name = historicalexposure>citation | url = https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20070010704_2007005310.pdf | title = Space Radiation Organ Doses for Astronauts on Past and Future Missions | chapter = Table-4. Average dose (D) or dose-rate recorded by dosimetry badge and estimates of the effective doses, E received by crews in NASA programs through 2004 | first = Francis A. | last = Cucinotta | page=22 | accessdate = 1 February 2014</ref> (150 mSv per year), although frequent crew rotations minimize risk to individuals.<ref>Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/935213314|title=The cosmic compendium : space medicine.|last=W.|first=Anderson, Rupert|others=[printer not identified]|isbn=9781329052000|location=[Place of publication not identified]|oclc=935213314</ref> A study published in 2005 in the ''International Journal of Impotence Research'' reported that short-duration missions (no longer than nine days) did not affect "the ability of astronauts to conceive and bear healthy children to term."<ref name=china/>  In another experiment, the frog Xenopus laevis successfully ovulated in space.<ref>Ronca, p. 218.</ref>

Radiation shielding has been noted as an issue for space colonization because children of female astronauts could be sterile if the astronaut were exposed to too much ionizing radiation during the later stages of a pregnancy.<ref name=tay/> Ionizing radiation may destroy the egg cells of a female fetus inside a pregnant woman, rendering the offspring infertile even when grown.<ref name=tay>cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/why-infertility-will-stop-humans-colonising-space-2213861.html | first = Jerome | last = Taylor | title = Why infertility will stop humans colonising space | newspaper = The Independent | date = February 14, 2011</ref>

The lack of knowledge about pregnancy and birth control in micro-gravity has been noted in regards to conducting long-term space missions.<ref name=Foster-139/>

While no human had gestated in space as of|2003|lc=on, scientists have conducted experiments on non-human mammalian gestation.<ref>citation | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7oUDEOPde8EC&pg=PA218| publisher = Elsevier Science B.V. | title = Advances in Space Biology and Medicine | volume = 9 | editor-first = Augusto | editor-last = Cogoli | isbn = 0-444-51353-1 | contribution = Mammalian Development in Space | first = April E. | last = Ronca | page = 219 |date=July 15, 2003 </ref> Space missions that have studied "reproducing and growing mammals" include Kosmos (rocket family)|Kosmos 1129 and 1154, as the Shuttle missions STS-66, STS-70|70, STS-72|72, and STS-90|90.<ref>Ronca, p. 222.</ref> A Soviet experiment in 1983 showed that a rat that orbitted while pregnant later gave birth to healthy babies; the babies were "thinner and weaker than their Earth-based counterparts and lagged behind a bit in their mental development," although the developing pups eventually caught up.<ref name=stier/>

=Childrearing=
A STS-90|1998 Space Shuttle mission showed that rodent Rat|''Rattus'' mothers were either not producing enough milk or not feeding their offspring in space.<ref>cite news | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-04-29/news/9804300176_1_baby-rats-joseph-bielitzki-space-shuttle-columbia-returns | title = Nasa To Probe The Deaths Of 51 Baby Rats In Space | date = April 29, 1998 | newspaper = Chicago Tribune</ref> However, a later study on pregnant rats showed that the animals successfully gave birth and lactated normally.<ref name=stier>cite web | url = http://curious.astro.cornell.edu/153-people-in-astronomy/space-exploration-and-astronauts/the-future-of-human-spaceflight/960-can-a-human-give-birth-in-space-intermediate | first = Sabrina | last = Stierwalt | title = Can a human give birth in space? | date = May 2006 | work = Ask an Astronomer | publisher = Cornell University</ref>

To date no human children have been born in space; neither have children gone into space.<ref name=stier/> Nevertheless, the idea of children in space is taken seriously enough that some have discussed how to write curriculum for children in space-colonizing families.<ref>citation | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9ogsP-CW3h4C&pg=PA65| editor-first = Ulrike  | editor-last = Landfester | editor2-first = Nina-Louisa | editor2-last = Remuss | editor3-first = Kai-Uwe | editor3-last = Schrogl | editor4-first = Jean-Claude | editor4-last = Worms | title = Humans in Outer Space: Interdisciplinary Perspectives | page = 65 | first = Alan | last = Britton | contribution = A school curriculum for the children of stace settlers</ref>

=Radiation=
File:Bernal sphere interior.jpg|thumb|Men and women fraternize in a Bernal sphere space colony; the Bernal sphere has a curved shape which was intended to aid in containing air pressure and to provide optimum mass-efficiency for radiation shielding for a human outer space colony.<ref name="ONeill" >O'Neill, Gerard K. ''The High Frontier: Human Colonies in Space'', third edition. Apogee Books, 2000.</ref>
Like modern space-travel, air travel exposes people on aircraft to increased radiation from space as compared to sea level, including cosmic rays and from solar flare events.<ref name=davis/>

The United States FAA requires airlines to provide flight crew with information about cosmic radiation, and an International Commission on Radiological Protection recommendation for the general public is no more than 1&nbsp;mSv per year.<ref name=davis/> In addition, many airlines do not allow pregnancy|pregnant flightcrew members, to comply with a European Directive.<ref name=davis/> The FAA has a recommended limit of 1&nbsp;mSv total for a pregnant woman, and no more than 0.5&nbsp;mSv per month.<ref name=davis/>

Massive particles are a concern for astronauts outside the earth's magnetic field who receive solar particles from solar proton events (SPE) and galactic cosmic rays from cosmic sources. These high-energy charged nuclei are blocked by Earth's magnetic field but pose a Health threat from cosmic rays|major health concern for astronauts traveling to the moon and to any distant location beyond the earth orbit. Highly charged HZE ions in particular are known to be extremely damaging, although protons make up the vast majority of galactic cosmic rays. Evidence indicates past SPE radiation levels that would have been lethal for unprotected astronauts.<ref>cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn7142|title=Superflares could kill unprotected astronauts| first = Stephen | last = Battersby | work = New Scientist | publisher =  Reed Business Information Ltd. |date=21 March 2005</ref>

A trip to Mars with current technology might be related measurements by the Mars Science Laboratory which for a 180-day journey estimated an exposure approximately 300 mSv, which would be  equivalent of 24 CT scan|CAT scans or "15 times an annual radiation limit for a worker in a nuclear power plant".<ref>cite magazine | url = http://www.space.com/24731-mars-radiation-curiosity-rover.html | title = Calculated Risks: How Radiation Rules Manned Mars Exploration | first = Sheyna E. | last = Gifford | magazine = Astrobiology Magazine | publisher = National Aeronautics and Space Administration | date = February 18, 2014 | access-date = January 7, 2017</ref> German standards for pregnant woman set a limit of 50 mSv/year for the gonads (ovaries) and uterus, and 150 mSv/year for the breasts.<ref>cite web | url = https://www.euronuclear.org/info/encyclopedia/r/radiation-exposure-dose-limit.htm | title = Radiation exposure, dose limits, Germany | work = Glossary of nuclear terms | first = Winfried | last = Koelzer| publisher = European Nuclear Society | date = January 2011 | access-date = January 7, 2017</ref> For pregnant woman, radiation increases the risk of childhood cancers for the fetus.<ref>citation | url = http://www.aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/174552/MI-Clinician-Factsheet.pdf | format = PDF | title = Radiology Clinician Fact Sheet: Radiation Information | publisher = NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation | date = September 2012 | access-date = January 7, 2017</ref>

One of the problems with radiation exposure from spaceflight for pregnant women is that children they bear might not themselves be able to have children.<ref name=tay/> When a child is still in the womb, the baby's developing reproductive organs are sensitive to radiation; a fetus of either gender could be rendered infertile.<ref name=tay/> The female fetus is vulnerable in that the eggs that develop while her mother is pregnant can be damaged, so if she has children, they could be infertile due to the exposure in their maternal grandmother's womb.<ref name=tay/>

